<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="718" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[801,1394,1977,2406]" lastBlockId="10.[188,1395,2411,3114]" pageId="10" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[802,1060,2175,2208]" pageId="10" pageNumber="718">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 190 mm, tail 180 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Dorsum of the Sanghir Squirrel is a rich chestnut-brown, venter varies from dark brownish to brownish buff, and tail is blackish. It can be distinguished from other species of similar size by absence of ear tufts, presence of middorsal stripe, and nape patches.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="718" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[188,1395,2411,3114]" pageId="10" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[190,301,2490,2523]" pageId="10" pageNumber="718">Habitat.</emphasis>
Secondary and primary forests, up to elevations of ¢.1000 m and probably higher. The Sanghir Squirrel also inhabits plantations and gardens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
